subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis
. 
Female
. Macropterous. Mesosoma and head concolorous, dark brown with weak metallic lustre (
Fig. 1
); gaster mostly brown except for partly white to hyaline Gt1. Legs and scape brown-yellow to variably darkened but at least following brown: meso- and metacoxae, profemur on posterior and metafemur on anterior surface, scape basally and apically on dorsal and outer surfaces. Head not conspicuously modified, convex, with lower parascrobal region passing smoothly into gena (
Figs 9, 10
). Clypeus protuberant, convex, apically serrate (
Fig. 9
). Scrobal depression deep, with sloping, non-carinate sides, smooth and shiny except for superficially sculptured scrobes and reticulate along outer margins (
Figs 9, 10
). Frontovertex between ocellar triangle and scrobal depression reticulate (
Figs 9, 10
). Mesoscutum reticulate virtually to posterior margin (
Fig. 13
). Mesoscutellum and axillae differentiated and distinct, scutellum slightly convex (
Fig. 13
). Acropleuron reticulate. Fore wing in larger specimens comparatively uniformly infuscate from base to apex (
Fig. 15
).

Male
. Body brown with weak violet lustre visible under some angles of illumination (
Fig. 2
). Head in exact dorsal view (
Fig. 71
) 4.5–4.7× breadth of an eye measured along a transverse axis as in figure 73. Frontovertex between ocellar triangle and scrobal depression partly reticulate, with cells slightly depressed mesally or/and imbricate (
Fig. 70
). Scrobal depression including scrobes smooth and shiny except for superficially sculptured outer margins (
Fig. 70
). Funicle with first segment plus strongly reduced anellus 2.2–2.5× as long as wide (
Fig. 63
). Mesoscutal midlobe reticulate to, or almost to, posterior margin, though less distinctly so in small specimens; lateral lobe reticulate (
Fig. 18
). Mesoscutellum coriaceous except reticulate near anterior margin and imbricate to indistinctly reticulate laterally. Metascutellum transverse-ovoidal, with lateroventral corners abruptly sunken (
cf
. 
Fig. 68
). Fore wing stigma as an elongated rectangle; uncus frequently almost to fully as long as height of stigma (
Fig. 58
).
